## 6. NAVIGATION DESIGN RULES

### 6.1 Desktop Navbar
- Logo left, nav links center or left-adjacent, CTA button right
- Max 5–6 top-level nav items. More than 6 creates cognitive load.
- Font size: 14px–16px, medium weight (500)
- Use clear active states: underline, color change, or dot indicator
- CTA button must be visually distinct from nav links (filled, rounded, contrasting)

### 6.2 Mobile Navbar
- Hamburger icon right-aligned, logo left-aligned
- Full-screen or slide-in drawer. Not a dropdown that pushes content down.
- Menu items large enough to tap: minimum 48px touch target
- CTA button must appear prominently in the mobile menu
- Close button clearly visible

### 6.3 Mega Menu
- Use only when there are 6+ service/product categories
- Organize in columns. Use icons or short descriptions for each item.
- Add a featured CTA card in the right column (e.g., "Book a Free Strategy Call")
- Close on click outside, Escape key, and tab-out

### 6.4 Service Dropdowns
- Show on hover (desktop) and click/tap (mobile)
- Keep to max 8 items per dropdown
- Use consistent icon + label + optional short description format
- Group logically by category if needed

### 6.5 Sticky Navbar
- Navbar becomes sticky after 80px of scroll
- Apply backdrop-blur and subtle background/shadow when sticky
- Logo may shrink slightly when sticky (transition with CSS)
- CTA button remains visible in sticky state

### 6.6 Transparent-to-Solid Behavior
- Hero sections with full-bleed backgrounds: start navbar transparent
- On scroll past ~60px: transition to solid or frosted-glass background
- Use CSS transition: `background-color 0.3s ease, backdrop-filter 0.3s ease`
- Ensure text contrast works in both states

### 6.7 Accessibility
- All nav items keyboard navigable
- Dropdown items accessible via keyboard arrow keys
- Use `role="navigation"` and `aria-label="Main navigation"`
- Focus state visible on all items
- Skip-to-content link at top of page (visually hidden, visible on focus)

