## 7. SECTION DESIGN SYSTEM

### 7.1 Problem Section
**Goal:** Make the target user feel deeply understood.  
**Layout:** Full-width section with a dark or accent background to break visual rhythm. Use large headline + supporting paragraph + 3-column pain point breakdown.  
**UI:** Icons or emoji to represent each pain. Short 1–2 sentence descriptions. Bold the pain, soften the explanation.  
**Conversion:** Agitation. The user must think "This is exactly what I'm dealing with."  
**Avoid:** Generic pain points that could apply to any business. Vague language.

### 7.2 Solution Section
**Goal:** Position the product/service as the natural, obvious answer.  
**Layout:** Mirror of problem section. Light background to signal relief. Headline + paragraph + benefit list or feature split.  
**UI:** Use a before/after split, a process visual, or a bold promise headline.  
**Conversion:** Relief and hope. The user must think "This could work for me."  
**Avoid:** Jumping straight to features before establishing the emotional shift.

### 7.3 Services Section
**Goal:** Communicate scope and depth of offering.  
**Layout:** Grid of service cards (2–3 columns desktop, 1 column mobile). Or: numbered list with large titles and descriptions.  
**UI:** Each service card has: icon or visual, service name (H3), 2–3 sentence description, optional link.  
**Conversion:** Build confidence in breadth and expertise.  
**Avoid:** Long paragraphs in service cards. More than 8 services without grouping.

### 7.4 Features Section
**Goal:** Show what the product does and why each feature matters.  
**Layout:** Alternating feature rows (image left / text right, then reverse). Or: tab-based feature explorer. Or: scrolling feature list with sticky visual.  
**UI:** Feature name (H3) + benefit statement + short description + optional screenshot.  
**Conversion:** Demonstrate capability without overwhelming.  
**Avoid:** Feature lists without benefits. Screenshots with no labels or context.

### 7.5 Benefits Section
**Goal:** Answer "What's in it for me?"  
**Layout:** 3-column or 4-column grid of benefit cards. Alternately, a large 2-column layout with icons.  
**UI:** Bold benefit headline + 2-sentence explanation. Optional: a relevant number or stat.  
**Conversion:** Translate features into outcomes the user cares about.  
**Avoid:** Repeating features disguised as benefits. "Powerful dashboard" is a feature. "See all your data in one place and save 4 hours a week" is a benefit.

### 7.6 Process Section
**Goal:** Reduce friction by showing how working together is simple.  
**Layout:** Numbered steps (horizontal on desktop, vertical on mobile). 3–5 steps maximum.  
**UI:** Step number (large, styled) + step title + 1–2 sentence description. Optional: icon per step.  
**Conversion:** Remove "this sounds complicated" objection.  
**Avoid:** More than 5 steps. Vague step names like "Step 1: Discovery."

### 7.7 Testimonials Section
**Goal:** Social proof through real client voices.  
**Layout:** 3-column card grid, or a large featured quote with smaller supporting quotes.  
**UI:** Quote text (larger, italic or styled) + name + role + company + optional photo or logo.  
**Conversion:** Trust. Specificity is critical — vague testimonials convert poorly.  
**Avoid:** Anonymous testimonials. Short quotes with no specifics. Stock photos as testimonial avatars.

### 7.8 Case Studies Section
**Goal:** Prove results with real data.  
**Layout:** 2-column card grid with project image, client name, category tags, and a result stat.  
**UI:** Hover reveals a short summary or "View Case Study" CTA.  
**Conversion:** Credibility and aspiration. The user sees what success looks like.  
**Avoid:** Case studies with no numbers. "We helped them grow" is not a result.

### 7.9 Pricing Section
**Goal:** Communicate value, reduce sticker shock, and guide toward the right plan.  
**Layout:** 3-column pricing cards. Middle card highlighted (most popular).  
**UI:** Plan name, price, billing period, feature list, CTA button, optional annotation ("Best for teams").  
**Conversion:** Make the decision easy, not overwhelming.  
**Avoid:** Too many plan options (max 4). Feature lists over 8 items without grouping.

### 7.10 FAQ Section
**Goal:** Answer objections before they become bounce triggers.  
**Layout:** Accordion. 2-column on desktop, 1-column on mobile.  
**UI:** Question as label. Answer expands on click. Keep answers under 100 words.  
**Conversion:** Objection handling. SEO value (FAQ schema).  
**Avoid:** FAQs that don't address real objections. More than 10 FAQ items on one page.

### 7.11 Final CTA Section
**Goal:** One last, powerful invitation to act.  
**Layout:** Full-width section with high contrast background. Centered. Headline + subtext + CTA button.  
**UI:** Make this section feel different from the rest of the page — use a color, gradient, or pattern.  
**Conversion:** Last chance to convert. Make it feel urgent and personal.  
**Avoid:** Repeating the hero CTA word-for-word. Weak closers like "Get in touch."

### 7.12 Footer
**Goal:** Navigation fallback, trust signals, legal compliance, SEO signals.  
**Layout:** 4–5 column grid on desktop. Stacked on mobile.  
**UI:** Logo + tagline, site links, service links, contact info, social icons, legal links, copyright.  
**Conversion:** Not a conversion section — but a trust signal. A well-designed footer signals professionalism.  
**Avoid:** Footer that is the same black-box on every project. Missing contact information.

