## 13. RESPONSIVE DESIGN RULES

### 13.1 Mobile-First Approach
Write base styles for mobile. Use `min-width` media queries to add desktop enhancements.

```css
/* Base: mobile */
.hero { padding: 64px 16px; }

/* Desktop enhancement */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .hero { padding: 128px 32px; }
}
```

### 13.2 Grid Conversion
```
Desktop:  3-column grid        → Tablet: 2-column grid   → Mobile: 1-column stack
Desktop:  2-column feature row → Tablet: 2-column        → Mobile: 1-column stack (image below text)
Desktop:  4-column pricing     → Tablet: 2×2 grid        → Mobile: 1-column stack
```

### 13.3 Typography Scaling
Use `clamp()` for fluid typography:
```css
h1 { font-size: clamp(36px, 5vw, 72px); }
h2 { font-size: clamp(28px, 4vw, 48px); }
body { font-size: clamp(16px, 1.2vw, 18px); }
```

### 13.4 Navigation Behavior
- Hide desktop nav items at < 768px
- Show hamburger icon
- Full-screen or drawer overlay mobile menu
- Sticky header on mobile always

### 13.5 Button Behavior
- Primary CTA: full-width on mobile
- Secondary CTA: full-width or 50% on mobile
- Minimum touch target: 44px × 44px for all interactive elements

### 13.6 Image Handling
- Use `srcset` and `sizes` attributes for responsive images
- Use `aspect-ratio` to prevent layout shift during load
- Use `object-fit: cover` inside fixed-height containers
- Lazy load all below-fold images

### 13.7 Avoiding Horizontal Overflow
- Use `overflow-x: hidden` on `body` only as a last resort — debug the actual cause
- Ensure no element has a fixed width wider than the viewport
- Use `max-width: 100%` on images and embeds

### 13.8 Touch Target Sizes
- Every tappable element: minimum 44px × 44px
- Space between touch targets: minimum 8px
- Never place two tappable elements within 8px of each other

---

## 14. ACCESSIBILITY RULES

Accessibility is not optional. It is a baseline requirement.

### 14.1 Semantic HTML
- Use `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`
- Use `<h1>` through `<h6>` in correct hierarchical order
- Use `<button>` for interactive elements, not `<div>` or `<span>`
- Use `<a href>` for navigation, `<button>` for actions

### 14.2 Heading Order
- One `<h1>` per page
- `<h2>` for section titles
- `<h3>` for card titles and subsections
- Never skip levels (no jumping from H1 to H4)

### 14.3 Image Alt Text
- Every `<img>` must have `alt` attribute
- Decorative images: `alt=""`
- Informational images: describe the content, not "image of..."
- Product images: describe product name, color, key feature

### 14.4 Keyboard Navigation
- All interactive elements reachable and activatable via keyboard
- Tab order must follow visual reading order
- Dropdown menus navigable with arrow keys
- Modal opens with Enter, closes with Escape

### 14.5 Focus States
- Default browser focus style is often insufficient — enhance it:
```css
:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--color-primary);
  outline-offset: 3px;
  border-radius: 4px;
}
```
- Never use `outline: none` without providing an alternative focus style

### 14.6 ARIA Usage
- Use ARIA only when native HTML semantics are insufficient
- `aria-label` for icon-only buttons
- `aria-expanded` for toggles and accordions
- `aria-live` for dynamic content updates
- `role="dialog"` and `aria-modal="true"` for modals
- Never use ARIA to fix broken semantic structure — fix the HTML first

### 14.7 Form Labels
- Every input must have a visible `<label>` associated via `for`/`id`
- Never use placeholder text as the only label
- Error messages must be associated with the input via `aria-describedby`

### 14.8 Color Contrast
- All text: minimum 4.5:1 ratio against background (WCAG AA)
- Large text (18px bold+): minimum 3:1
- Use a tool like WebAIM Contrast Checker before shipping

---

## 15. SEO AND AEO STRUCTURE

### 15.1 Heading Structure
- One `<h1>` per page — the primary keyword phrase
- `<h2>` for each major section — secondary keywords
- `<h3>` for subsections and card titles
- Never put keywords in headings unnaturally — write for humans first

### 15.2 FAQ Sections
- Add FAQ sections to service pages, product pages, and local landing pages
- Each question as `<h3>` or `<dt>`, answer as paragraph or `<dd>`
- Add FAQ schema markup (JSON-LD) for rich snippets

### 15.3 Schema Markup (JSON-LD)
Always implement:
- `Organization` — name, logo, URL, contact
- `WebPage` or `WebSite` — name, URL
- `LocalBusiness` — for local service pages (NAP, hours, service area)
- `Product` — for e-commerce pages
- `FAQPage` — for FAQ sections
- `Article` — for blog posts
- `BreadcrumbList` — for all interior pages

### 15.4 Internal Linking
- Every service page links to related services
- Blog posts link to relevant service pages
- Footer includes key service and location page links
- Homepage links to all primary service pages

### 15.5 Metadata Placeholders
Every page template must include:
```html
<title>{Page Title} | {Brand Name}</title>
<meta name="description" content="{150–160 character description}">
<link rel="canonical" href="{canonical URL}">
<meta property="og:title" content="{OG Title}">
<meta property="og:description" content="{OG Description}">
<meta property="og:image" content="{OG Image URL}">
```

### 15.6 Avoid
- Text inside images (not crawlable)
- Duplicate H1 tags
- Generic meta descriptions ("Welcome to our website")
- Pages with no H2 structure
- Shipping a Vite SPA where every route hides the real `<h1>`, primary copy, and meta tags behind a delayed client-only render with no `react-helmet-async` (or equivalent) updates — crawlers and previews still need a coherent default in `index.html` plus per-route `<title>`, description, canonical, and OG tags for share cards

---

## 16. PERFORMANCE RULES

### 16.1 Images
- Use WebP format (or AVIF) for all images
- Use `srcset` for responsive images
- Set explicit `width` and `height` to prevent CLS
- Lazy load all below-fold images: `loading="lazy"`
- Hero image: eager load, preload in `<head>`
- Max image dimensions: 1920px wide for backgrounds, 800px for content images

### 16.2 Fonts
- Load only the weights you use
- Use `font-display: swap`
- Prefer variable fonts when using multiple weights
- Preload critical fonts: `<link rel="preload" as="font">`
- Host fonts locally when possible (eliminates third-party DNS lookup)

### 16.3 JavaScript
- Code-split by route: in Vite + React, use `React.lazy` + `<Suspense>` with `react-router-dom` routes, and/or `import()` for heavy route-level chunks; Vite emits separate chunks automatically — verify with `vite build` output and `rollup-plugin-visualizer` (or similar) when bundle size matters
- Defer non-critical scripts
- Avoid render-blocking scripts in `<head>`
- Remove unused JavaScript — audit with bundle analyzer
- Use dynamic `import()` for heavy libraries

### 16.4 CSS
- Purge unused CSS in production (Tailwind does this automatically)
- Avoid `@import` in CSS (causes sequential loads)
- Critical CSS inlined in `<head>` for above-the-fold content

### 16.5 Core Web Vitals Targets
```
LCP (Largest Contentful Paint): < 2.5s
INP (Interaction to Next Paint): < 200ms
CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift):  < 0.1
```

### 16.6 Animation Performance
- Use `transform` and `opacity` for animations (GPU-composited)
- Avoid animating `width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, `padding`, `margin` (cause reflow)
- Use `will-change: transform` sparingly and only on animated elements

